  <li id="comment-33817" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.eatingwithassholes.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Carly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=419#comment-33817"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2012-04-19T23:21:35-04:00">Thursday, April 19, 2012 at 11:21 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>These bars look so, so good. I love baking with heartier flours.  I think a lot of sources turn people off from it by making a big deal of telling people that anything but AP or cake flour will result in disaster.  While obviously you can&#39;t always do a straight substitution with a whole grain flour for a recipe designed for AP, but many of my friends who are not huge bakers read those admonitions as &#8220;baking always means using white flour.&#8221;  </p>
<p>Even so, I&#39;ve never used rye flour in a sweet baked good, and I&#39;m excited to try it.  I&#39;ll make these this weekend.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='index.html?p=419#comment-33817' data-commentid="33817" data-postid="419" data-belowelement="comment-33817" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Carly" aria-label='Reply to Carly'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-33907" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.eatingwithassholes.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Carly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=419#comment-33907"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2012-04-19T23:21:35-04:00">Thursday, April 19, 2012 at 11:21 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>These bars look so, so good. I love baking with heartier flours.  I think a lot of sources turn people off from it by making a big deal of telling people that anything but AP or cake flour will result in disaster.  While obviously you can&#39;t always do a straight substitution with a whole grain flour for a recipe designed for AP, but many of my friends who are not huge bakers read those admonitions as &#8220;baking always means using white flour.&#8221;  </p>
<p>Even so, I&#39;ve never used rye flour in a sweet baked good, and I&#39;m excited to try it.  I&#39;ll make these this weekend.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
